    • Method Detail

      • rollPlayer

        void rollPlayer​(Player player,
                int initialDelay1,
                int finalDelay1,
                int delayIncrement1,
                int initialDelay2,
                int finalDelay2,
                int delayIncrement2)
        Roll the dice progressing from the initialDelays to the finalDelays
 in increments specified by the delayIncrements
 
 NOTE: All delays are in milliseconds (ms)
 
 1. dice are initialised at their random starting face
 2. for each die start at initialDelay then increment the delays for each die on each iteration
 3. call GameEngineCallback.playerDieUpdate(...) for each die separately
 4. continue until both delays >= finalDelay 
 5. call GameEngineCallback.playerResult(...) to finish
 
 See Also:
  GameEngineCallback.playerDieUpdate(Player, Die, GameEngine)
  GameEngineCallback.playerResult(Player, DicePair, GameEngine)
        Parameters:
        player - the Player to roll for
        initialDelay1 - the starting delay in ms between updates for die 1 (reflects the speed at which this die is rolling across the table)
        finalDelay1 - the final delay in ms between updates when the die has come to rest
        delayIncrement1 - how much die 1 slows down (i.e. delay gets longer) after each individual tumble i.e. each iteration until current delay > finalDelay
        initialDelay2 - same as initialDelay1 but for die 2
        finalDelay2 - same as finalDelay1 but for die 2
        delayIncrement2 - same as delayIncrement1 but for die 2
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - thrown when:
        • any of the delay params are < 0
        • either of the finalDelay < initialDelay
        • either of the delayIncrement > (finalDelay - initialDelay)

        NOTE: for assignment 1 you can assume the values passed for the delays are the same for dice 1 and 2 and therefore optionally use only the first three delay parameters since event handling and/or threads are suggested to implement different rolling speeds which will be implemented in assignment 2

      • rollHouse

        void rollHouse​(int initialDelay1,
               int finalDelay1,
               int delayIncrement1,
               int initialDelay2,
               int finalDelay2,
               int delayIncrement2)
        Same as rollPlayer() other than the two notes below but rolls for the house and calls the
 house versions of the callback methods on GameEngineCallback, no player parameter is required. 
 
 IMPORTANT NOTE 1: At the end of the roll this method should iterate all players and 
 call applyWinLoss(Player, DicePair) to update each player's points
 
 IMPORTANT NOTE 2: After calling GameEngineCallback.houseResult(DicePair, GameEngine)  
 this method should also call Player.resetBet() on each player in preparation for 
 the next round
        Parameters:
        initialDelay1 - the starting delay in ms between updates for die 1 (reflects the speed at which this die is rolling across the table)
        finalDelay1 - the final delay in ms between updates when the die has come to rest
        delayIncrement1 - how much die 1 slows down (i.e. delay gets longer) after each individual tumble i.e. each iteration until current delay > finalDelay
        initialDelay2 - same as initialDelay1 but for die 2
        finalDelay2 - same as finalDelay1 but for die 2
        delayIncrement2 - same as delayIncrement1 but for die 2
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - thrown when:
        • if any of the delay params are < 0
        • either of the finalDelay < initialDelay
        • either of the delayIncrement > (finalDelay - initialDelay)

        See Also: GameEngineCallback.houseDieUpdate(Die, GameEngine) GameEngineCallback.houseResult(DicePair, GameEngine)

      • applyWinLoss

        void applyWinLoss​(Player player,
                  DicePair houseResult)
         A player's bet is settled by this method 
 i.e. win or loss is applied to update betting points 
 based on a comparison of the player result and the provided houseResult
 
 NOTE: This method is usually called from rollHouse(int, int, int, int, int, int) 
 as described above but is included in the public interface to facilitate testing
        Parameters:
        player - - the Player to apply win/loss to
        houseResult - - a DicePair containing the house result
